title: you mean I wasted a whole day's vacation so you could ask me ...
text: On March 16, 2016, I called Electrolux to request a warranty repair of my then 10-week old dishwasher.  The phone rep asked numerous questions, including what, exactly, was wrong with my dishwasher.  She then instructed me how to try to "reset" the dishwasher (which failed), and then she scheduled what I thought was a repair appointment, five days later on March 21.  The rep asked me whether I preferred a repair time window of 8:00 a.m. to Noon, or Noon to 5:00.  I said I preferred morning as I had an afternoon appointment.  The rep then told me that Whitman Appliance Repair would contact me the day before to tell me my specific appointment time.  The day before, sure enough Whitman called, only to tell me that would see me between 10:00 a.m. and 2:00 p.m.  I said that Electrolux scheduled me for 8:00 a.m. to Noon.  Whitman said they could come between 10:00 and 2:00, or they could reschedule for a later date.  So at the last minute, I had to schedule an entire vacation day off work, and reschedule my afternoon meeting.  On March 21, Whitman arrived as scheduled.  The repair technician walked into my house, looked at my dishwasher, and said, "what's wrong with it?"  I said, "didn't Electrolux tell you?"  The technician said, "they don't tell us nothing."  I explained the problem.  He then said, "you need a new blah blah blah" (a part).  "We'll have to order it, it will arrive in 3 to 10 business days.  Then we will call you to schedule the repair."  He then took a few pictures of my dishwasher, including a picture of the serial number.  He was in my house for all of about 30 seconds.  I said, you mean I wasted a whole day's vacation so you could ask me the exact same question that I already answered for the Electrolux phone rep?"  He said, we'll, I needed to get the serial number."  I said, "I needed to tell the phone rep the serial number before she would schedule the repair!"  He said, "I also needed to take pictures of your dishwasher to document any pre-existing damage, so you can't sue us to fix something that wasn't our fault."  Great!  I blew an entire vacation day so that Electrolux and Whitman Appliance Repair could cover their butts.  Finally, on March 29 -- 19 days after I called Electrolux, I got to schedule yet another vacation day and my dishwasher was finally repaired.  The complete lack of even basic communication between Electrolux and Whitman and the long (half-day) appointment windows for repair convince me that Electrolux and Whitman Appliance have absolutely no regard for customer service.  I will think long and hard before I ever buy another Electrolux appliance.  NEW TOPIC:  The dishwasher I replaced was a very low-end model.  The Electrolux was, at $888 retail, what I thought was a mid-to-high range model.  It has a stainless steel interior and a third rack, which I liked.  However, I learned the expensive way that a more expensive dishwasher does NOT clean my dishes any better than a cheap one.  The ONLY real difference between my old dishwasher and the new Electrolux, is that the Electrolux is quieter when running.  However, the noise level of my old dishwasher never bothered me or my family.  Or bedrooms and TV room are separate floors from the kitchen, so we rarely heard the old dishwasher.  And even if we were sitting nearby, we could converse or play music or do whatever without ever being bothered by the dishwasher.  If I ever have to buy another dishwasher, I'll choose a cheap one (and very lucky NOT an Electrolux).

title: Small but Mighty
text:
Used this for about two months now and am loving it in my tiny apartment with no W/D hookups (or room for a w/d anyway, ha). It's been absolutely excellent for the price. I wish I could tell everyone at the laundromat about it. That being said, it is a small washer and you can't expect it to be capable of the same things as a full size machine. Treat it right, and it should last.

What are the steps?
The basic order is either wash in the washer -> drain -> rinse in the washer -> drain -> spin dry in the dryer - OR - wash in the washer -> transfer clothes to the dryer and fill for a rinse (conserving your washer water for another load) -> drain dryer and dry. You can either rinse in the washer or the spin bucket, so you are able to re-use your washer water if doing multiple loads.

Pros
> Gets your clothes clean. I feel like my clothes are cleaner with this than a laundromat washer, ha.
> Runs relatively quietly (There is the sound of water, and a light humming while it spins).
> Slim size fits in/on top of many places
> Lightweight. I'm a 130 lbs marshmallow and have no problem lifting it (without water in it, ofc)
> Fast...wash cycles run ~12 minutes, rinse ~9, and dry ~9.
> SO much more convenient than leaving the house to do laundry
> Eventually pays for itself if you don't otherwise have access to a free washer/dryer.

Cons(?) More like, things to be aware of and how to work around them:
> I can't stress enough, this is not a full-sized machine. You can't work it like a traditional large, sturdy, metal washer. It makes a light burning plastic smell with larger loads, & I've never filled it higher than about halfway between the Med and High fill lines out of fear of over-stressing the motor. Not made to do all your weekly laundry in one day (unless it's a single person's maybe), but more like 2, 3 loads max a day...meaning multiple laundry days a week may be needed. This is in order to preserve the life of your machine becaaauuusseee...
> The only -actual- con: this company seems unresponsive with inquiries about replacements/repairs, as other reviewers have noted.

> Must elevate to drain properly. If the drain hose makes the water travel against gravity at any point (i.e. UP), it won't drain all the way. I've remedied this by putting it on a storage tub to drain ~90% and then lifting it a couple inches to completely drain the rest.

> No heated dryer. Spin dryer does get clothes about 90~95% dry though, much dryer than just-out-of-the-wash. I was in disbelief when I first used it, ha. To prevent stiff clothes, add a bit of white vinegar to your washer run. It's a little stiffer than your usual heated dryer, but not like you paid for starch at the dry cleaners. It hasn't bothered me at all.

> How...do I...fill it? It does come with a hose but that probably won't fit your sink. I use the shower-head from my bath tub and fill it directly. Others fill buckets and then pour in the water from there. Others have bought adapters for -make- the hose fit their sink. Others utilize the dustpan sink funnel technique

> It's super noisy/wobbly/chaotic! = It's probably overloaded. Aside from the first and last ~7 seconds of the spin dryer, it shouldn't be moving much at all. Neither tub should be filled to the top; your clothes need room to move!

text:
Bought this a little over a year ago. It worked fine, but then failed recently. Decided to go OEM and then saw how this aftermarket igniter failed.

The first photo shows how it melted through the housing. When I replaced the original Wolf igniter with this cheaper version, the old housing was perfect - lasted 14 years. One year later, igniter fails and the housing is badly damaged. My guess is that the resistance was too low, thereby drawing too many amps, getting too hot, and burning itself and other parts up.

The second photo shows the OEM replacement. Wolf supplies not only an igniter, but replacement brackets and housing. Good thing since my older housing was melted. It also has much longer leads which can be easily pulled into the electrical connector area beneath the cooktop. No need to have wire nuts exposed in the oven now.

The OEM version is three times the price, but lasts 10 times longer and doesn't pull too much power and melt things. Just glad that it didn't burn out an electrical module controlling things in the process. Cheaper is not better in this case.

text: I bought these because they say they are the exact replacement for my refrigerator icemaker filter.  They fit and remove and install exactly the same.  They look alike and they feel alike.  However...  When my light flashed on to replace the filter, I easily replaced it with the spare that came with the fridge.  No issues.  Then I ordered these to have on hand when needed.  About 8 months later (we use a lot of ice and filtered water).  The light started flashing so I replaced it easy as pie with one of these.  I will note that when I tried to flush it with water, the water came out in my cup BLACK!!! It was like this for a good 4 or 5 minutes of running water through the filter.  The ones that came with the fridge never did this..  So once it was running clear, I was happy with my purchase.  However, a couple days later, I noticed that my ice was black.  I dumped it and let the water run through the water on the ice maker water valve.  It ran clear.  I had to dump 2 more bins of ice to get clear ice again..  This took several days to clear it up.  So, still not a deal breaker on these filters.  Then about 2 weeks later, the filter light signal began to flash that it needed to be changed AGAIN.  I removed the filter, drained it and replaced it thinking that it could not be dirty already.  I  ran water through it and it was running clear so I let it flash for a week or 2 longer.  I decided to replace the filter and  the second one out of the 3 pack also ran black water for a few minutes until it finally cleared up. I am one month into using the second filter and the light has came on again.  This is now a bargin if it has to be replaced more often than the originals that came with the fridge.  I will be trying another brand when these are gone..  Do they work?  Yes,  Are they cost effective for the savings if you have to replace them more often?  No...

text:
Updating initial five star review: Like this unit a LOT. Original purchase late June 2017. Returned after four months it due to an apparent malfunction of the descaling sensor/light. Performed lengthy descaling process no less than 12 times but the light never turned off. Did not know if descaling complete or unity malfunctioning.

REGISTER your unit for warranty service!

Advise those who have problem with their single serve coffee brewer or any other Cuisinart product, to contact the company by phone. I first tried an email to the company asking for assistance but the advice proved ineffective.
The CS rep listened to my report of the problem and promptly issued a ticket for a new replacement brewer. UPS picked up the old one four days after my contact.The new unit was promised within 7-10 days of my call I received it today 11-17-17, 7 days later.

Likes: appearance, large volume water reservoir, water filter, number of options for brew size, brew temp, brewing speed (it is fast!), options to make just hot water for tea, soup and hot chocolate, cleaning cycle function, programming for various other preferences, clarity of user instructions in manual and unit controls, 3 year warranty, and many other neat features. A three year warranty is a bit surprising given that most electronic devices have only a one year length. I think $120 for the unit is reasonable. $100 and up seems to me to be the starting point for better quality single cup brewers.

Love the versatility of this machine!

Want to make espresso? Why buy an espresso machine when this will do it? Take a dark roast coffee, Italian, French or any other and brew on 4 ounce setting. Whoa! Close enough to true espresso without the special grinding, packing the brew unit and clean up.

If a dark roast K cup is still too strong brewed on the 12 oz., setting, the leave it in and brew again on 4 oz., and you have a perfect cup of lighter dark roast.

Based on function, quality of build and warranty service I recommend this product.

title: Redesign Has Pluses and Minuses
text:
I ordered two of these to replace a couple of older ones because the lids cracked in half (see photo). I've had four or five of these lids break along the left side, up to the red disc. Happens every time after a few months of use. Anyway, I haven't had the new ones long enough to see if they too will break, but I'm not a fan of the redesign. The new design has a wire basket with a lid, like the old one, but the basket then goes inside a plastic shell with a single hole in the bottom. So preparing one for use requires two steps instead of one, and cleaning is a pain. The old basket had a "handle" that I used to rap on the edge of a bowl to shake the grounds loose (I save my grounds for gardening). The new basket lacks the handle and is generally sort of flimsy, making it difficult to empty.
Also, the new design allows you to make either a cup or a carafe. Okay, not a bad idea, except that now you have to go through another menu, in which you must select either a picture of a carafe or a number, 1-6; then you get to another screen where you can select the size. There's really no explanation of what the numbers mean (I know, it's probably in the Keurig manual somewhere) so we just guess and then see what we get.
The whole thing is annoying. Amazon is famous for reducing transactional friction; it's disappointing when a company goes out of its way to increase friction.
On the plus side, a cup of coffee seems to brew more quickly. Haven't actually timed the two models, but it feels faster.
Regarding Keurig customer service: I recently posted a question about the cracking lids, and someone from Keurig suggested that I call customer support. I did, and it was a waste of time. The rep took all my personal info down and said he would pass it on to someone else who might be able to do something about replacing the broken lids. Or not, he wasn't sure. That was the last I've heard from them.

title: most durable, not easiest to clean
text:
I've tried three kinds of refillable pods for the Keurig 2.0: this one, the ones made by Keurig, and a generic purple plastic kind. There are two factors that set them apart: durability and ease of cleaning. This one (the metal Fill 'n Save) appears to be the most durable, although I've owned it for the shortest time, so I could be proven wrong. However, the weaknesses of the other two are caused by their plastic construction. The purple plastic ones are flimsy. The tops are barely held on by a plastic hinge that is destined to break after a few dozen uses; also, one bent almost in half after I banged it against a plastic garbage container trying to get the used coffee grounds out.
The pods made by Keurig are made of sturdier plastic, and the tops screw on. However, of the three that I bought, one top is cracked and another came apart--the filter fell off the bottom. This filter can be reattached, but it falls off almost every time it is used.
So I would say that the metal version is destined to be more durable; however, I have to give the edge to Keurig for "cleanability," and this is a crucial factor, because the only real reason to use disposable pods is that you don't have to clean them. The Keurig wins this point because the pod has a little handle, just big enough to hold onto while you rap the container against the edge of a garbage can (or in our case a ceramic bowl that we use to collect the grounds, which are later sprinkled on our Azaleas). Also, the detached lid means the lid doesn't get in the way while you're trying to knock the grounds loose.
In sum, I prefer the Keurig because ease of cleaning is crucial. Although two of three are somewhat broken, they are still usable. If cleanability doesn't matter to you because you rinse your grounds down the disposal, you might prefer the metal version. The purple ones are much cheaper, but they're almost designed to be disposable, which partially defeats the purpose of buying refillable pods.
